metadata.name: Isola della Scala #16
metadata.description:
All things pass, all things flow,
Movement, connection, separation, all in tow.
A misstep and we're knocked off course,
But in the end, we rise, as if by force.
Like a dance of dominoes, we fall and we stand,
In this ever-changing world, we're a part of the grand.

The name of this work is the name of the city where my roots began, where the path of everything changed and new directions in life were taken.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love

Brushstrokes are synthesized using a large number of small lines of varying opacity, hue, and brightness. There are five styles : blocks, curves, lines, blur and partial blur; 9 color palettes, and several additional features controlling the composition of the piece.

p5.js script

metadata.name: f-emerald #222
metadata.description:
f-emerald generates unique ephemeral crystal-like structures that morph in space. each generation has a different shape, animation and colour palette. 

the crystals flicker with colours in the dark most of the time. there is, however, a 20% chance of obtaining a crystal on a bright background with a light colour palette and one out of ten structures is created in black and white.

metadata.name: Tech Eclipse #13
metadata.description:
The impact of progress on our world is so large-scale that even the vast majority of catastrophes that can only be imagined will not completely erase the traces of technology.

The apocalypse will overshadow us, our achievements and plans. But it is not able to erase our trace completely. And, like the crown of the sun, faint traces will remind us that this was not just a planet, and we were not just organisms.

metadata.name: Scalabili-TREE  #67
metadata.description:
Scalabili-TREE 
Growing up and adapting to the world!

For the Decentralized Autonomous Education (https://linktr.ee/cubiclearn) (DAE) project they asked me to represent the concept of "scalability" with an artwork.
Scalability is one of the ten principles on which the DAE project is based. The other nine principles were represented by nine other artists.

To represent the concept of scalability in a visual way, with a generative algorithm, I was inspired by nature and plants.
I represented this concept through the growth rings of trees, drawing shapes that evoked the section of a cut tree. Each ring represents the growth of the tree and its ability to adapt to the environment while continuing to function efficiently.
This can involve a variety of different strategies, for example the tree can increase root depth and branch out to support a larger canopy, or develop mechanisms to conserve water and nutrients to survive in a dry environment
One key aspect of scalability in trees is the ability to adapt to changing environmental conditions over time.

The work was created through the construction of a generative algorithm that designs each ring starting from the center, gradually adding the outer layers, exactly as the tree itself would do.

Everything is generated with code.
This work uses p5.js library and c2.js library.

metadata.name: NEBELWALD #42
metadata.description:
NEBELWALD is the first series of about 10 different tree/flower generative art works, which have come together over the last 10 years. 

This project explores a minimalist approach to tree naturalism using a recursive algorithm and includes three traits: a density layer of fog, a measure of tree growth, and the softness of snowfall.

Press [s] in live view to download a high resolution png.

Artist notes:

Since I moved to Wandlitz, north of Berlin, in the middle of the "Naturpark Barnim" (https://www.barnim-naturpark.de/), in 2003,
I've done a lot of exploring nearby nature. In addition to the beautiful lake and heath landscapes, I fell in love with the wild acacia forests. These strange trees, sometimes more like huge wild grasses, grow so wildly into each other.

Once I experienced it in a dense fog, which was amazing! beautiful and mysterious at the same time. This has definitely inspired the NEBELWALD work series.

While playing around with different branching system code snippets, a more and more complex image composition came together. The final script for this project on fx(hash) was finally given more randomness for a wider range of different outputs and an additional random grain filter.

Project link: http://lumicon.de/e-art/project/nebelwald/

Many thanks to jesse (jbird) for the good collaboration, which ultimately made it possible to get this work released.

metadata.name: Oxygen #4
metadata.description:
Oxygen makes strange forms of life thrive even in the darkest of places.

This is a generative piece using curated randomness to create textures, generate distortion fields, simulate growth and create compositions.

The work is best viewed in high resolution, but due to the time it takes to render, the preview image is capped to only 1000 pixels in height. You can change the resolution by pressing keys

- 'm' for medium  (height=2000px)
- 'l' for large (height=3500px)
- 'x' for extra large (height=5000px) 

outputs. 

Press 's' to save the output as a PNG file.

For even larger outputs, you can open the work in live mode and append the text '?size=10000' to the URL. Here, you can change the number (10000) to the desired height in pixels. 

Please note, that a very high-resolution image may take a very long time to render and some browsers are not able to save the image. However, even a 10000 pixels tall outputs have been generated during testing.

metadata.name: Planetarium #114
metadata.description:
Francesco Forcellini, November 2022, Milano, Italy.
Compositions of spheres made with grids, proportions, symmetries and  broken symmetries,  order and casualties.


To save an image with the size of the window press S once the image is fully rendered.
To save a Hi-Resolution image 6000px x 8000px press H and wait, the page will reload and start to render.


Published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.
Built using p5js,a custom WEBGL shader and a shader with a modified version of "cnoise" by Stefan Gustavson.
See the License.md for license details.
